  "statement": {
    "markdown": "Given a collection of intervals, merge all overlapping intervals. An interval is defined by a start and end value, for example [1,3]. The intervals [1,3] and [2,6] overlap because they share some common range, in this case, the range [2,3]. If we merge these intervals, we get [1,6]. Your task is to write a function that takes a list of intervals as input and returns a new list where all overlapping intervals have been merged. The input list of intervals will be in the format [[a,b],[c,d],[e,f]] where a,b,c,d,e,f are integers and a<=b, c<=d, e<=f. The intervals may not be in any specific order. The function should return the merged list of intervals in any order. For example, given the input [[1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]], the function should return [[1,6],[8,10],[15,18]].",
    "inputFormat": "The first line contains a single integer N, the number of intervals. The second line contains N pairs of space-separated integers, where each pair represents an interval.",
    "outputFormat": "The output should be a list of merged intervals, where each interval is represented as a pair of space-separated integers.",
    "notes": "The input intervals are not guaranteed to be in any specific order. The function should be able to handle overlapping intervals, as well as non-overlapping intervals.",
