  "editorial": {
    "title": "Merging Overlapping Subintervals Efficiently",
    "intuition": "The key observation is that sorting the intervals by their start values allows us to merge overlapping intervals in a single pass. This is because if an interval's start value is greater than the end value of the last merged interval, it cannot overlap with any previous intervals.",
    "bruteForce": "A brute force approach would involve checking every interval against every other interval for overlap, resulting in a time complexity of O(N^2). This is inefficient for large inputs.",
